<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The sun hung low on the horizon in the crisp Autumn air, staining the skies delicate shades of amber and violet. The gentle wind had the slightest bite to it, precursor of the coming winter.  I would have never noticed it before, but now every scent, each facet of reality, was alive with importance.  When a bird chirped hesitantly from the north, my eyes leapt unerringly in its direction, making sure it was indeed a bird.  Bird calls, Thorfinn had told me, made some of the best coded signals in the world; easy to overlook, easy to imitate.  It took great concentration to remain aware of the call of every bird, the movement of every stone.  But it was a price I was willing to pay.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I noticed, too, that my teacher's eyes, like mine, never ceased their roaming; but neither did they miss any detail.  We glided through the dusk like twin shadows, leaving no mark of our passing.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Do you think -&quot; I began, but a glare silenced me.  Thorfinn unlimbered one of his big, dirty hands and gestured, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Use the Cant.  You need more practice.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I nodded, moving my left hand through the sequence of coded movements.  It had been the slower of my two hands to learn thus far.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Do you think we have been followed?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Thorfinn shook his head.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Not the way we've come,</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> he gestured back.  The surety of his gestures betrayed total certanity.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Even if we were tracked to the eastern regions, our trail would have gone cold in the canyons.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Still,</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> I replied silently, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> I don't like leaving loose ends.  She might not be safe with Bayle's troops.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Why didn't you leave one of your own men with her, then?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> He raised one eyebrow, even as his little finger hooked in the question gesture.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> I did,</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> I admitted.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Chemistrius is watching her.  And Zachton is close by, if there's any trouble.  But we know Kane has men in the tower.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp And we know Linarius knows who they are,</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> he replied.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Even if he does not know who </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->you<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  are.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I nodded - I had thought it best that the fewer knew my identity, the better.  I had dealt with many old friends who still believed I was dead.  I ran my fingers through my white hair and sighed, but knew there was no help for it; it would be at least another year before I could walk as a human again without fear of being recognized.  Memories were still too fresh.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> It is still difficult to bear decieving those who were once my friends,</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> I signaled.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> And even more difficult to convince them to trust a dark elf.  It is a good thing Kagato's faction has become so influential.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp It would be unwise to trust in it too heavily, </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->my teacher replied sternly.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Were it not for the letter from Ulrich, he would not have trusted either of us.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp And Ulrich would not have sent the letter were it not for your father's memory, </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->I reasoned.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> And yours.  </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->Thorfinn's gesture was sharp.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp My hand went still, lapsing into silence as I continued to pace alongside the hulking barbarian.  His black armor, like mine, made no sound, even at a fast clip, and the plates bent like supple cloth when we moved.  Karadin had told me the armor was made of woven shadows, and did not quite obey the physical laws of Norrath as solid metal should.  The method of its construction was a closely guarded secret, never divulged on pain of death to any but the most trusted of mages.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp A few months ago, Zarar had sought me out, wanting the shattered remnants of the abhorrent gargoyle that I had gathered up after its death.  Half the fragments had gone into the construction of the suits of armor we all wore now; the other half had disappeared without a trace.  I would have looked more closely at his doings, but the Militia and the Coalition had been closing too quickly; another day in Freeport and they would have found me.  I clenched my fist helplessly as I remembered Moro's dying words.....&quot;They have been my undoing, Arafein....do not let them be yours.&quot;<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp My teacher's eyes noticed my movement, small though it was.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> What is it?<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Just a stray memory, </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->I replied.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Moro told me that the power games in Freeport would kill me as they killed her.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Only if you let them.  </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->His tone was dismissive.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Lucan is dead.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Elsin is a powerful enemy, </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->I reminded him.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> And we can be sure she knows much of what Nestral knew.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp How much did Nestral know?  </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->He seemed surprised.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I grimaced.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Too much.  She knew about the mark.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp And about you?  </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->His other hand closed around the hilt of his dagger.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I shook my head.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Not enough to endanger either of us.  But enough to make Elsin suspicous.  We should have killed Nestral earlier.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Why?  It wouldn't have mattered.  We're not the only ones the Coalition knows is looking for the mark.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The last thing we need is more attention, </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->I gestured vehemently.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Nestral knew me too well; she might have been able to track us.  But that's not something she could have imparted to Elsin.  If House T`Gaza still existed, things would be even worse.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp And you still don't think we were followed?  </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->His eyebrow rose again.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I gritted my teeth in frustration.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> That's what I'm trying to tell you.  If she was still alive, we would have been.  I wouldn't have gone near Freeport in the first place except to be sure of her.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp And to be sure of Dushire's contract.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I grimaced, but I let it go.  Doubtless, Thorfinn still thought that had been a mistake on my part.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The flat land of the northern plains of Karana were fast giving way to the gentle rolling hills of the western region beneath our strides, and the sun dipped lower into the horizon as we moved toward it.   Before long, the settlement of Zek would be behind us, and the rendezvous point would be close.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp We glided through the sparse brush covering the hills in absolute silence, always avoiding the fading beams of sunlight that lanced down through the branches.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Who is our contact? I signaled as we traveled.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp An outcast from the White Rose, the scout said, </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->he replied easily.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Other than that, I have no idea.  Which is why you are here.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The scout said to come alone? </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->I guessed.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Thorfinn nodded.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> You'll have to watch my back, in case this is a trap.  Don't let the contact see you if you can help it.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp And the backup plan?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp He shrugged.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> A lie is more convincing when it's partially true - if something goes wrong, we'll just tell him it was part of your training.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp I couldn't help but nod - it made perfect sense to me.  All I had to do was play the part of an inept beginner.  The fires of the Zek encampment flashed briefly past us, then were gone.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The moon was just beginning to rise when the threadbare tents of the brigand camp melted out of the darkness before us.  I turned to Thorfinn, making the gesture for a general question.  At his nod, I fell back, letting him outpace me by at least fifteen strides, then began to follow him, slipping in and out of the shadows of the trees as though they were pools of water.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp As my teacher approached the camp, he held his arms out in a gesture of defenselessness, looking about him curiously.  I wasn't fooled - once, he had set his weapons on the ground and placed a blanket over them, then asked me to attack him before he could disarm me.  Although my strike was perfect, my hand had arrived at its target totally empty; I had stared at it in shock for a moment before he had flipped up the blanket to reveal a blank patch of floor, then pointed to his belt.  Both his daggers had still been in their sheaths; he had disarmed me with a hidden knife up his sleeve.  But one thing didn't sit well with me - the camp was totally empty.  If our contact was nearby, I could not sense him.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Thorfinn's head turned slowly - first in one direction, then another.  Suddenly, he stopped, and sniffed the air curiously.  The instant he did so, I also became aware of the new scent; someone had arrived, and had most likely stepped into the airflow upwind from us on purpose to let us know.  I hoisted myself silently into the foliage of a particularly large spruce and crouched on one of the lower branches, peering intently into the camp as the newcomer strode boldly into the deserted camp.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp He seemed at first glance to be an ordinairy barbarian, but as soon as he came within handshaking distance of Thorfinn I realized my error - he was only about five feet tall, unusually short for one of his race.  His beard and hair were streaked with gray, but he still looked very hale and alert.  I noted the daggers on his belt with more than a passing interest, even as I strained my ears to hear the conversation.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;You sent a message for me?&quot;  Thorfinn asked, the picture of innocence.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The small barbarian nodded.  &quot;McLanis knows who you are, and gave me your name a few years ago.  I thought we might be able to discuss some business matters.&quot;<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Hospitality before commerce,&quot; Thorfinn commented, &quot;seems to be a thing of the past these days.&quot;<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The other looked baffled for a moment, then shrugged.  &quot;As you will.  I'm called Vilnius the Small, and I know who you are, Wayforger.  Your work has drawn great admiration in the eastern circles.&quot;  &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Thorfinn bowed, choosing to ignore the obvious falsity of the complement.  &quot;Very well, Mr. the Small....how can I aid you?&quot;<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The shorter barbarian seemed to bristle a bit, but didn't take the bait.  Turning away, he gazed coldly out at the empty plains for a few moments before speaking again.  &quot;A courier of mine went to make an appraisal in Qeynos three days ago; I've had no word of her.&quot;<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &quot;Then it is likely she is dead,&quot; reasoned my teacher blandly.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Vilnius shrugged.  &quot;Perhaps.  Or she may have gone to ground.  Either way, I'm in need of someone to find out.  You come very highly recommended.&quot;<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Thorfinn neither moved nor spoke.  After a few brief moments of silence, the smaller barbarian looked back over his shoulder at my teacher.  &quot;Well?&quot;<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The taller barbarian shrugged.  &quot;You're going to need to be a bit more specific than that.  Unless you want to pay double the fee to cover my investigative expenses.&quot;<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp Vilnius scowled for a moment, muttering under his breath.  I shifted my weight slightly to lean a bit closer, careful to keep the stress of my weight off the weaker parts of the branch; perhaps a fifty-fifty chance of the branch creaking.  If I made a sound, Vilnius would doubtlessly discern my presence instantly.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The branch remained silent.  After a moment, he turned back to Thorfinn and hurled words at him like daggers.  &quot;Very well.  Her name is, or perhaps was, Malka Rale.  She was sent on an errand for me concerning the Circle of Unseen Hands.  What errand that may be, you don't need to know.&quot;  Thorfinn raised an eyebrow, but said nothing.  &quot;She was carrying an item that should have been returned to me.  If she is alive, obtain it from her - if she is dead, take it from her corpse.  But bring the item to me.&quot;<br>
